1

Worked all day and late into the evening on the omiltemanus group; descriptions and calculations. Made satisfactory progress, with a few interruptions a/c foot ball games. Should be able to finish omiltemanus in one more day

Notes:

pamg

There are no dates indicated on the pages of this journal - only page numbers. The date for this entry is January 1, 1951.

28

Worked all day and evening on lepidus and made real progress. Begin to see daylight on this difficult species. The first draft of lepiduslepidus is now complete; and the material to finish Klauberi is compiled and organized.

Notes:

pamg

48

Worked all day on the taxonomic section, incorporating in the check-list and key (section 17) the data accumulated in the studies of Mexican rattlers] thus far completed. Made good progress.

Went to Scholia Club in the evening.

Notes:

pamg

Date 2-17-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:00 AM
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:00 AM

49

Continued with the taxonomic section and finished bringing it down to date. Checked the specimens lately received from the Mexican National Museum and incorporated them in the write-ups. A fairly good day in net accomplishments.

Notes:

pamg

56

Worked all day and evening on durissus and made good progress. Looks as if there were a new subspecies in the northwest, with the Michoacan specimens in the vicinity of Uruapan as the most extreme.

Notes:

pamg

Date 2-25-51

59

Tried to north on the 11:45 train. Had been a wreck on the line so had to take a stage and did not arrive until 3:50 instead of 2:30. Missed a meeing of the board of the Insurance Co..

Went to the L.A. Public Library and worked from 4:15 until 8, picking up several items.

Notes:

pamg

Date 2-28-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:10 AM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

60

Meeting of the Light and Power Council in the morning, and until 2:15. Spent the afternoon in my room and did a little writing on durissus, basiliscus etc. Left on the Lark at 9 P.M.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-1-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:11 AM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

61

Attended a meeting of the California State Chamber of Commerce in the morning. Left for U.C. at 2:10. Worked at MVZ for a while. Saw Benson, Zweiful, Richardson, and a number of others. Was greatly disappointed in finding the 4 specimens of durissus from Chilpancingo were spoiled so little information could be gained from.

Then worked in the UC libraries until 6:30 and cleared up a few items.

Not a profitable day. Too much interruption.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-2-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:15 AM

Drove down from LA this morning. Worked all afternoon on miscellaneous catching up.

Out to dinner in the evening.

70

Worked from 7 AM to 10 PM on the molossus - nigrescens problem. Made good progress. No more scale counts should be necessary. Now for tabulations and write-ups.

76

Worked all day from early morning until late evening on molossus making special scale counts and territorial pattern surveys. Made good progress.

Outfitted Sams for his Sonora trip.
___________________________________________________
Shaw's trip to Borrego

Found an apparently starved Dipsosaurus at Clark Dry Lake. Seemed to have been killed, partly swallowed and regurgitated by a leopard lizard that was caught, but couldn't prove it.

Cold trip. Almost nothing seen.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-17-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:25 AM
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:24 AM

77

Worked all day on molossus - nigrescens. Made color and pattern notes by states and groups. Then started to tabulate the characters.

Notes:

pamg

83

Spent the morning rechecking questionable scale counts in Molossus & nigrescens. Went to a Zoo Director's meeting at noon.

Continued with co4rrected counts in the afternoon.

Spent the evening tabulating.

Brattstrom returned this evening.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-24-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:29 AM
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:28 AM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

84

Spent the morning again studying the boundary between molossus and nigrescens; also the relationship between molossus and basiliscus in southern Sonora. Can they be subspecifically related? Do they hybridize?

Spent the evening making calculations of averages.

Now have all the date that can be secured from the specimens at hand for the molossus - nigrescens write-up.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-25-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:31 AM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

Page Edit History:

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:31 AM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

87

Left for Los Angeles on the 7:45 train.

Attended the annual meeting of the stockholders of the Founders Insurance Co at 11 AM.

Went out to the LA Museum at 1:30. Made counts on their 4 specimens of molossus until 4 P.M. Their collection is in worse shape than ever.

Worked in the LA Public Library from 4:30 to 6. Picked up a few items.

Left for San Francisco on the Lark.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-28-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:34 AM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

88

In San Francisco all day. Went to Chickering and Gregory; then to the Light and Power Council.

Spent from 2:30 until 5:30 at the California Academy picking up the new head counts and other items on molossus, basiliscus, and durissus.

Caught the Lark at 9.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-29-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:36 AM

pamg

90

Worked on the molossus write-up all day and evening and made fair progress.

Bobby Meanley returned from his 2 weeks in Sonora. The season was not yet started but he got a few good specimens.
_____________________________________________________________
[{Shaw]]'s trip to Borrego.

Saw a cally at Clark's Dry Lake
Temp 61 degrees at 6:05 P.M.
Ran the road from 6:47 (63 degrees) to 8:10 (54 degrees). 35 miles, 1-3/4 hrs. Nothing seen. Was 47 degrees at 8:26 at Scissors Crossing.

Notes:

pamg

Date 3-31-51

  • pamg 11/03/2012 12:40 AM

91

Good progress today'; finished the first draft of molossus - nigrescens.

Talked to the Episcopalian Youth League on rattlesnakes in the evening and then went to a concert.

Notes:

pamg

97

Worked all day and late into the evening on the changes necessary in triseriatus by reason of having received the data on the type specimen of triseriatus Wagler, 1830, still on hand at the University of Berlin Museum 9 Russian Zone 0.

Notes:

pamg

Date 4-7-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/04/2012 02:52 PM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

98

Again worked all day and evening on the revision of the triseriatus exposition to make the changes necessitated by the date from Berlin proving that the type of triseriatus was applicable to the southern subspecies. This section ( triseriatus and aquilus ) is now much more complete and better co-ordinated then it was before.

Notes:

pamg

143

Spent the day at Berkeley. Saw Stebbins, Miller, Benson, Zweifel, Woodin, Gorman and many others.

Worked on specimens in the morning.

Took lunch with the bunch at their regular Wednesay gathering in the luncheon hour.

Zweifel told me how he had been bitten by a mitch in the Riverside Mts and lost the index finger on his hand. He had given the snake nembutol to kill it and thought it dead, but it succeeded in imbedding one fang.

Worked in the library from 1:30 to 9:20 and cleared up a number of items. Then returned to SF.

May 31 Continued

1 Sonora (striped) L DOR 12 mi W. of Wickenburg on US 60. Maricopa Co., Ariz. greasewood desert. Saved squirming. Got to Wickenburg at 6:50. Clear and breezy. Had supper and called Dr. Shannon. Went to his house, and saw his collection. He leaves to join the Army tomorrow. Gloyd had left for the East. The collected at OPCNM and had good luck. Shannon has made good progress with his paper on the Reptiles of Ariz., but the Army will slow this up. He has a good collection, but no Mexican rattlers.

Left Wickenburg at 8:05. Almost dark. Lots of traffic to Congress Junction. May have missed something. The weather was perfect. Thereafter drove fast. Prescott at 9:50. Clear and cold. Miles today 412.

Started for the convention of the Edison Electric Institute at Denver at 11 AM this morning. Went out via Highway 80 to Yuma, thence north to Prescott, where we spent the night at the Prescott Motor Inn. 152

Left Prescott this morning at 8:40. It was clear, cold, and breezy, and continued the same all day, although somewhat warmer at the lower altitudes. Not a single live snake or lizard was seen all day.
1 desert racer M DOR Granite Dells, Yavapai Co grass

Turned off her to go to Flagstaff via Jerome, Clarksburg and Oak Creek Canyon. A fine drive but poor for reptiles.
1 desert racer L DOR Entro, Yavapai Co, grass
1 red racer L DOR Lonesome alley, 10 mi E. of Granite Dells, Yavapai Co., grass. No black on head
1 Gopher affinis small DOR same place. Saved.
1 Gopher L affinis DOR 6 mi. S. of Jerome, Yava Co. rocky gorge; trees.

It was clear and warm at Jerome; an interesting old mining town.
1 P.c. affinis L DOR Clarksdale, Yava Co Rocky desert
1 P.c. affinis L DOR Cottonwood, Yava Co Mesquite desert

This was the last snake seen today. It was cold and windy most of the way; warm, windy and dusty the rest.

Arrived at Flagstaff at 11:40 Cold and windy. Left at ---- Drove fast the rest of the way. Many gas stations try to attract people by long rows of large signs depicting various attractions, particularly rattlers. (Continued on May 29th)

153

Today we drove from Alburqueque to Colorado Springs via Santa Fe, Taos, Costilla, San Luis, Fort Garland (got gas) , La Veta Pass, Walsenburg, and Pueblo. Left at 8:45 and arrived at 7:10. There was rain from Walsenburg in. Stopped for quite a while in Santa Fe.

Only one DOR snake was seen and no other reptiles, alive or dead. Mostly high plateau, mountains. Too early for anything to be out above about 5000ft.
1 Gopher DOR Bernalillo, Sandoral co., NM fields.
Total miles today 357.
Anyway had a good snake dinner tonight.

Phoned Leet about Allie's condition from Albuquerque.
Because of the rain there was a big demand for auto courts, (despite a good supply) and we were lucky to get one, although not too good.

Notes:

pamg

Date 6-2-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/06/2012 08:55 PM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

154

Today we left our auto court at 9:20. It had snowed last night, and there was snow on the car. We drove through Manitou Springs and up the mountain road a ways, but
it was cold and threatening snow. Then drove around through the Garden of the Gods; then down to the Broadmoor for lunch. Stayed around the hotel for awhile and then drove to Denver where we arrived at 4:45 and put up at the Brown Palace Hotel. Strolled around after dinner. Met a number of Edison Institute people.

Miles today 137.

Notes:

pamg

Date 6-3-51

155

This morning after registering for the convention and meeting a lot of old friends, went to the Public Library. Talked with Eastlake the librarian ad then worked the catalogues. Picked up some interesting items, some of which will have to be followed up later.

Went for a drive in the afternoon and to the Natural History Museum. Had a talk with Walker Van Riper, about the rattlesnake strike and associated matters. Very interesting indeed. Saw some of the residence section of the community.

Went to a G. E. dinner at the Park Lane Hotel tonight.

Notes:

pamg

157

Attended the Edison Electric Institute meeting in the morning and a meeting of the top utility executives at noon. This lasted until 3. Went to the Public Library at 3:30 and worked until 5:30, when the Western Research room closed. Picked up a number of good leads.

Date 6-6-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/06/2012 11:22 PM

158

Went to the final sessions of the EEI Convention from 10 to 12; then to Rotary for lunch.

Started home from Denver at 1:20, and arrived at Grand Junction, Colo, at 8:30 after several stops along the way, including Loveland Pass, 11992 ft. It was warm at Grand Junction but nothing was seen on the road -- in fact not a reptile alive or dead the whole day.

West of the divide, at least from Glenwood Springs on, the country seems entirely suitable for rattlers. I was surprised at the lack of DOR.

After a very late supper, we put up at the Frontier, the best motel we have seen on this trip.
______________________________________________________________
(June 8th, continued)

Jumped a deer on the road W. of Long Valley Junction. It had been dark after seven.

Looks as if there were a number of passes low enough to permit intergradation between decolor and lutosus, between the Price-Emery and the Ephraim-Marysvale areas. The valleys are extensively cultivated. The rattlers must live up in the rocks. This certainly needs more study.

Notes:

pamg

Date 6-7-51

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 11/06/2012 11:31 PM
  • BPOC 09/17/2012 05:32 PM

159

Started home from Grand Junction at 10:40, after tending to various chores in town. The first 20 miles are through cultivated lands, where there should have been gopher snakes, but weren't. From there to Green River is a high rolling plateau, increasingly arid and alkalie as one proceeds westward. Sometimes there were large rocks piled along the roadside where lizards should have perched but none were seen. It was warm and part cloudy. We reached Green River at 12:50 and Price at 3:10. Here we turned southward instead of going up to Springville or Spanish Fork as originally planned. We went south through Castle Dale and Emery, and then turned northwest to Salina. From here we went south again on 89 to Lone Valley Junction and thence west to Cedar City over the mountains.

1 P. c. deserticola L DOR 3 mi. E. of Salina, Sevier Count. Sagebrush. Perfect deserticola marks on the head.

Reached Salina at 5:45, and Cedar City at 9:50. Miles today 445. The driving was hard in some areas because of roads under construction or twisty mountain driving.

(Continued on June 7)

Notes:

pamg

Date 6-8-51

160

Having missed Cedar Breaks yesterday as we passed through that area in darkness, we went there this morning. A beautiful view. A Forest Ranger told me rattlers were found up to 8500 feet at Mesa Verde.

We again left Cedar City at 11:10 homeward bound. Lunched and got a telegram at St. George. Saw a few lizards on rocks between St. George and the Nevada state line --the first seen in a long time.

1 snake ( patch-nose?) lost on the road at Wheaton Spring, S.B. Co., the only live snake seen on the entire trip.

Reached Yermo at 7:15; warm but not hot. Started the evening drive at 7:55 going west on U.S. 466 from the 466-91 junction.

Kramer Junction 466-395 at 8:50; dark. 1/4 moon. 75 degrees F., little breeze.

Adelanto at 9:50 68 degrees

1 Kingsnake M DOR (saved) 2 mi D. of Adelanto. Millers Corner (jnct 395-66-91 ) at 10:10 64 degrees.

A very disappointing evening drive. Maybe too cool. They weren't out as shown by lack of DORs. The traffic was heavy. Reached San Bernardino at 11:00 Cool.

(continued on June 10)

Notes:

pamg

161

Started home from San Bernardino this morning at 8:00 and arrived at 10:10. At least 3 DOR's were seen, one in SD Co, but didn't stop because of high speed.

Spent the afternoon (3 hours at the office) and evening trying to catchup. What a prospect.

Miles today 114.

349

Worked today on house repairs and miscellaneous items so didn't get much done on the book.

Had a long Zoo director's meeting this noon. They reiterated their intention to publish the book, even if it went as high as $20,000.

Talked at the Scholia Club this evening on "Is The Chamber of Commerce Crazy" really on population growth and problems.

350

Spent the entire day and evening checking recent rattlesnake arrivals. Made a few changes in the Mexican taxonomic paper as a result. Got this material co-ordinated. All complete now except terrificus. Within a week or so will decide whether to proceed further with this or drop it.

357

Worked hard all day and until about 7 when I was too tired to continue. Made good progress on terrificus. Made all counts and special pattern and color surveys of the specimens I have at hand. Decided that I could separate the Sao Paulo population from the others on pattern, thus separating out cascavella or cumanensis, but probably will not actually make the segregation.
